&lt;p&gt;Apr 16 2021&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Naval:&lt;/strong&gt;
Does probability actually exist in the physical universe, or is it a function of our ignorance? If I&amp;rsquo;m rolling a die, I don&amp;rsquo;t know which way it&amp;rsquo;s going to land; so therefore I put in a probability. But does that mean there&amp;rsquo;s an actual probabilistic unknowable thing in the universe? Is the universe rolling a die somewhere, or is it always deterministic?&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>We Can’t Prove Most Theorems with Known Physics</title><link>https://linguage.github.io/naval/orig/we-cant-prove-most-theorems-with-known-physics/</link><pubDate>Wed, 14 Apr 2021 15:46:48 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://linguage.github.io/naval/orig/we-cant-prove-most-theorems-with-known-physics/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://linguage.github.io/naval/zh/we-cant-prove-most-theorems-with-known-physics.zh/"&gt;中文版本&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
